    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The light-dependent reactions occur in the thylakoid membranes and use sunlight to split water, release oxygen, and generate ATP and NADPH. These energy carriers then power the Calvin cycle, which takes place in the stroma and uses ATP and NADPH to fix carbon dioxide into sugar molecules. The main difference is that the light-dependent reactions capture light energy to create energy carriers, while the Calvin cycle uses those carriers to build glucose. Think of them as a two-step process where the first step fuels the second.",
