    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Calvin cycle has three main stages: carbon fixation, reduction, and regeneration. In the first stage, the enzyme RuBisCO attaches CO₂ to a 5-carbon sugar called RuBP, creating an unstable 6-carbon intermediate that immediately splits into two 3-carbon molecules. The second stage uses the ATP and NADPH from the light reactions to convert these 3-carbon molecules into glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate (G3P), which can be used to build glucose. Finally, most of the G3P molecules are recycled back into RuBP so the cycle can continue, while some G3P leaves the cycle to form sugars. Think of it as a conveyor belt that fixes carbon, powers it, and then rebuilds the starting material to keep the line moving.",
      "source": "target",
